JavaScript OOP – Core Concepts (with Pseudocode)
1. Class & Object

A class is a blueprint. An object is an instance of that blueprint.

Pseudocode:
Class Animal
    property: name

    method speak()
        print "Animal makes sound"

Create object dog from Animal
dog.name = "Tom"
dog.speak()
JS Reality:
class Animal {
    constructor(name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    speak() {
        console.log("Animal makes sound");
    }
}
2. Constructor

Special method used to initialize object properties when object is created.

Pseudocode:
Class Person
    constructor(name, age)
        set this.name = name
        set this.age = age

Create object p1 with ("Aman", 20)
3. Encapsulation (Data Hiding)

Restrict direct access to data. Use methods to control it.

Pseudocode:
Class BankAccount
    private balance = 0

    method deposit(amount)
        if amount > 0
            balance += amount

    method getBalance()
        return balance

Key idea:
→ Data is hidden
→ Access is controlled

4. Inheritance

One class inherits properties/methods from another.

Pseudocode:
Class Animal
    method speak()

Class Dog inherits Animal
    method bark()
JS:
class Dog extends Animal {}
5. Polymorphism

Same method name, different behavior depending on object.

Pseudocode:
Class Shape
    method draw()

Class Circle inherits Shape
    override draw() → "Circle"

Class Square inherits Shape
    override draw() → "Square"

For each shape in list
    shape.draw()

Key idea:
→ Same interface, different implementation

6. Abstraction

Hide unnecessary details, show only essential features.

Pseudocode:
Class Car
    method startEngine()  // internal logic hidden

User only calls:
car.startEngine()

In JS, abstraction is usually done via:

classes
private fields (#)
methods